entities.name: American Bulldog
entities.description: American Bulldogs are known for being excellent guard dogs, courageous, dependable, confident, steady, fearless, intelligent, easy to train, energetic, active, athletic, good with children, and having a short, easy-to-care-for coat.

entities.name: Exercise Needs
entities.description: American Bulldogs need a lot of exercise.

entities.name: Rambunctious and Rowdy
entities.description: American Bulldogs can be rambunctious and rowdy, especially as younger dogs.

entities.name: Territorial Behavior
entities.description: American Bulldogs can be territorial with larger dogs, especially of the same sex.

entities.name: Socialization
entities.description: American Bulldogs must be properly socialized as puppies to avoid aggression as adults.

entities.name: Willful and Stubborn
entities.description: American Bulldogs can be willful and stubborn if not shown strong leadership.

entities.name: Gassy and Drooling
entities.description: American Bulldogs can be gassy and drool a lot.

entities.name: American Bulldog
entities.description: The American Bulldog is a powerful and athletic all-purpose working dog, known for being fearless and steady guard dogs. They are typically gentle and loving family companions but may not tolerate other dogs, especially those of the same sex.

entities.name: Dental Disease
entities.description: Dental disease is the most common chronic problem in pets, affecting 80% of all dogs by age two. American Bulldogs are more likely than other dogs to have problems with their teeth.

entities.name: Tartar build-up
entities.description: Starts with tartar build-up on the teeth and progresses to infection of the gums and roots of the teeth.

entities.name: Infections
entities.description: American Bulldogs are susceptible to bacterial and viral infections such as parvo, rabies, and distemper.

entities.name: Obesity
entities.description: Obesity can lead to various health issues in American Bulldogs.

entities.name: Parasites
entities.description: American Bulldogs can be infested by fleas, ticks, ear mites, hookworms, roundworms, heartworms, and whipworms.

entities.name: Spay or Neuter
entities.description: Spaying or neutering decreases the likelihood of certain types of cancers and eliminates the possibility of unwanted puppies.

entities.name: Hip and Elbow Dysplasia
entities.description: An inherited disease that causes the joints to develop improperly and results in arthritis.

entities.name: Nerve Disease
entities.description: Neuronal Ceroid Lipofuscinosis (NCL) is a progressive neurologic disease found in American Bulldogs.

entities.name: Thyroid Problems
entities.description: Bulldogs are prone to hypothyroidism, where the body doesnâ€™t make enough thyroid hormone.

entities.name: Ichthyosis
entities.description: A severe flaking skin condition called ichthyosis, characterized by large dry flakes resembling fish scales.

entities.name: Eyelid Abnormality
entities.description: Entropion is a condition where the eyelid rolls inward, causing the eyelashes to rub against the cornea.

entities.name: Cataracts
entities.description: A common cause of blindness in older Bulldogs.

entities.name: Mange
entities.description: Demodex is a microscopic mite that lives in the hair follicles of dogs, causing skin issues.

entities.name: Bladder or Kidney Stones
entities.description: American Bulldogs are more likely to develop stones in the kidney or bladder.

entities.name: Respiratory Distress Syndrome
entities.description: Also known as brachycephalic syndrome, affects dogs with a short nose, like the American Bulldog.

entities.name: Routine Care, Diet, and Exercise
entities.description: Includes supervising the pet, grooming, brushing teeth, cleaning ears, and providing a proper diet and exercise.

entities.name: Pet Health Insurance
entities.description: Signing up for pet health insurance to cover medical tests and procedures throughout the dog's life.
